  "note_nemt_cet_TEM-8_1_word_0": "### Guidance\n\n**Sordid**, **Vile**, and **Morally**\n\n**Simple Words**\nIn the provided lists, **sordid** belongs to a group of words describing behavior and personality. While **sordid** can describe a place that is physically filthy, it is often used to describe actions that are \"dirty\" because they are dishonest or shameful. **Morally** (the adverb form of moral) describes how an action relates to standards of right and wrong. **Vile** is a word used to describe something that is extremely unpleasant or wicked.\n\nNote: The words \"vile\" and \"morally\" are not explicitly listed in the provided word lists.\n\n**Root and Suffix Analysis**\n- **Sordid**: From the Latin root *sord-* (meaning filth or dirt) and the suffix **-id** (which indicates a state or condition). It describes the state of being filthy.\n- **Morally**: The root is *moral* (from Latin *mos, mor-* meaning custom or habit) with the suffix **-ly** (which turns the adjective into an adverb). This describes the *manner* in which something relates to character or rules of conduct.\n- **Vile**: Comes from the Latin *vilis*, meaning \"cheap\" or \"base.\"\n\n**Multiple Meanings**\n- **Sordid**: Can describe a physically \"sordid\" apartment (full of trash) or a \"sordid\" business deal (full of lies).\n- **Vile**: Can describe a \"vile\" smell (disgusting to the senses) or a \"vile\" crime (disgusting to the conscience).\n\n**Analogy**\nThink of **sordid** or **vile** behavior as **mud on a white suit**. The suit represents a person's reputation or character. The mud is the action. Even if the suit is expensive and well-made, the mud makes the entire thing look \"dirty\" and \"degraded.\"\n\n**Diagram**\n[ Physical Dirt ]  --------> [ Becomes ] --------> [ Moral Dirt ]\n(Squalor/Trash)              (Metaphor)            (Sordid/Vile acts)\n\n[ Action ] + [ Standards of Right/Wrong ] = [ How it is judged **Morally** ]\n\n**Examples**\n1. The detective uncovered the **sordid** details of the theft.\n2. Living in such **sordid** conditions can affect one's health and spirit.\n3. He behaved **morally** by returning the lost wallet to its owner.\n\n**Socratic Questions**\n- If the root of **sordid** means \"dirt,\" why is it an appropriate word to describe a person who cheats others for money?\n- When we say someone is \"morally degraded,\" are we talking about their physical health (like in TEM2) or their character (like in TEM1)?\n\n【Recommended Resources】\n\n- YouTube: Vocabulary for morality and behavior explanation video  \n  [Watch](https://www.youtube.com/results?search_query=sordid+vile+morally+english+learning)\n\n- Quizlet: Flashcards for practice  \n  [Practice](https://quizlet.com/search?query=sordid+vocabulary)\n\n- English StackExchange: Community Q&A discussion  \n  [Explore](https://english.stackexchange.com/search?q=sordid)\n\n### Quiz\n\n1. Based on the root *sord-*, if a room is described as **sordid**, is it more likely to be filled with flowers or filled with grime?\n2. Which suffix would you add to the word \"moral\" to describe *how* a person acts in a way that follows good principles?\n3. In TEM1, **sordid** is grouped with words like **unwholesome** and **wretchedness**. What do these three words have in common regarding the \"feeling\" or \"tone\" they describe?",
